<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<body>
    <%- include('templates/header'); %>
    <%- include('templates/layout-header'); %>
    <igem-layout>
        <q-page padding>
            <div class="row justify-center">
                <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4">
                    <img v-if="!nightMode" class="responsive-image" src="http://2018.igem.org/wiki/images/4/40/T--Thessaloniki--team-logo.png">
                    <img v-if="nightMode" class="responsive-image" src="http://2018.igem.org/wiki/images/b/b8/T--Thessaloniki--team-logo-night.png">
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row justify-center gutter-md" :class="rM('text-dark', 'text-light')">
                <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-10 col-lg-10">
                    <q-timeline color="secondary" style="padding: 0 24px;" responsive>
                        <igem-timeline-entry icon="colorize" color="blue" side="left">
                            <div>
                                Gene expression is unpredictable, noisy and prone to perturbations,
                                thus posing a challenge towards designing reliable and functional
                                systems. One of the most decisive factors affecting the
                                functionality of synthetic biological systems is gene copy number
                                variation, that gives rise to variability in gene expression.
                            </div>
                            <template slot="side">
                                Image of Graph
                            </template>
                        </igem-timeline-entry>

                        <igem-timeline-entry icon="colorize" color="blue" side="right">
                            <div>
                                We provide <b>Galene</b>, a genetic toolbox that enhances system
                                stability by disassociating gene expression from copy number and
                                provides translational control of protein production.
                            </div>
                        </igem-timeline-entry>

                        <igem-timeline-entry icon="colorize" color="blue" side="left">
                            <div>
                                The former is achieved by implementing a type I incoherent
                                feed-forward loop network motif that consists of a regulatory
                                element which compensates for changes in copy number, thus
                                stabilizing the promoter. Through <a href="http://2018.igem.org/Team:Thessaloniki/Design">model-driven
                                    feedback</a>,
                                we accomplish promoter stabilization by utilizing 3 distinct
                                systems, each with its own advantages and appropriate uses.
                            </div>
                            <template slot="side">
                                Shape triforce
                            </template>
                        </igem-timeline-entry>


                        <q-timeline-entry heading>
                            CRISPR interference, TAL Effectors, transcriptional attenuator-interacting sRNAs
                        </q-timeline-entry>

                        <igem-timeline-entry icon="colorize" color="blue" side="left">
                            <div>
                                Going one step further, we implemented a theophylline aptamer that regulates translation and allows for the induction at the desired expression level.
                            </div>
                            <template slot="side">
                                (animation ?)
                            </template>
                        </igem-timeline-entry>

                        <igem-timeline-entry icon="colorize" color="blue" side="right">
                            <div>
                                As a proof of concept, we demonstrated the stabilization of a, previously inconsistent across different copy numbers, heterologous AND-gate system.
                            </div>
                        </igem-timeline-entry>

                        <igem-timeline-entry icon="colorize" color="blue" side="left">
                            <div>
                                In order to understand current problems in synthetic biology and enhance our project design we went beyond the lab and contacted researchers and experts from numerous fields. We also created Synapsis, a guideline on how to communicate science to people of different cultural and scientific backgrounds.
                            </div>
                            <template slot="side">
                                Synapsis image
                            </template>
                        </igem-timeline-entry>

                        <igem-timeline-entry icon="colorize" color="blue" side="right">
                            <div>
                                Following this guideline, we organized a Synthetic Biology tour in the Balkan Peninsula, where we visited 4 institutions in 3 countries, promoting Synthetic Biology and gaining valuable feedback.
                            </div>
                            <template slot="side">
                                <balcans-map></balcans-map>
                            </template>
                        </igem-timeline-entry>
                    </q-timeline>
                </div>
            </div>
        </q-page>
    </igem-layout>
    <%- include('templates/layout-footer'); %>
